          evP1: "At the event held in Byala, our patented equipment, the process of water cavitation, and its benefits were presented. Georgi Mishkov, manager of Cavitation System, and Professor Stoyanov from the Naval Academy in Varna explained how cavitation improves water quality by removing impurities and microorganisms. They also highlighted its important benefits for skin and athletic performance. The cavitation equipment uses high-energy pulses to create and break bubbles, leading to water purification. After the presentations, a discussion was held with the guests, who had the opportunity to ask questions and discuss the application of the technology.",
          evP2: "Learn more about us and cavitation:",
          evP3: "Georgi Mishkov",
          evP4: "Manager of Cavitation System",
          evP5: "Rumen Stoyanov",
          evP6: "Honorary Professor at the Naval Academy",

          cavT1: "What is cavitation?",
          cavT1P1: "Cavitation is the formation of air bubbles in water due to sudden changes in pressure‚Äîit's a process of disrupting the integrity of the liquid, occurring in those parts of the flow where the pressure decreases and reaches a critical value. With the formation of air bubbles and the change in their sizes during the cavitation process, the physical and acoustic properties of the water are altered.",
          cavT1P2: "During hydrodynamic treatment of water, its physical-chemical characteristics are altered. During this process, water molecules break down, releasing oxygen and hydrogen peroxide, which are powerful oxidizers. According to scientists, the 'cold boiling' of water can be compared to the action of a huge mixer.",
          cavT1P3: "When cavitation bubbles collapse, a certain amount of energy is released and the following chemical process occurs:",
          cavT1P4: "Water molecules become saturated with oxygen due to hydrodynamic changes. The fluid's characteristics alter its energy state and gain an additional degree of freedom. As a result, the water is disinfected, and microbes and bacteria are killed. Additionally, when the bubbles are neutralized, a large amount of energy is released, which can be used to heat the water. Cavitation treatment of the water allows for deep molecular processing while preserving biologically important microelements. The effectiveness of the bactericidal action depends on the intensity of cavitation and the duration of exposure. The quality of the input water, including turbidity, salinity, color, etc., does not affect the effectiveness of the process. Bacteria are simultaneously subjected to hydrodynamic, thermal, and shock effects, leading to the destruction of their surface and their elimination. The most intense destruction of microorganisms occurs at the moment of cavitation, and complete disinfection happens with the even distribution of water in the cavitation zones.",
          cavT2: "Purification of Liquids",
          cavT2P1: "Currently, reagent-free methods for liquid purification are promising. Reagent-free water purification methods do not pollute the natural environment with chemicals and do not have harmful or irritating effects on the human body upon contact. One of the promising methods for water purification is treatment in cavitation reactors. The bactericidal effect of cavitation is directly proportional to its intensity, frequency, or exposure time. The effect of cavitation on aqueous solutions is related to the separation of water molecules within the cavitation bubbles.",
          cavT2P2: "Passing water through so-called cavitation reactors",
          cavT3: "Cavitation in Water Purification",
          cavT3P1: "The intense impact of shock waves on bacteria such as Salmonella or E. coli can reduce their numbers by thousands of times. The effect of cumulative fluid jets during the collapse of cavitation microbubbles causes the death of bacteria. Evaluations of the effect of cavitation treatment on the viability of spores in a suspension of Fusarium solani and live cells of bacteria and fungi showed that after five cycles of treatment in a cavitation reactor (CVR), the number of spores was reduced by half, the number of live cells decreased by an order of magnitude, and the length of actinomycete mycelium was significantly reduced. After cavitation treatment of wastewater in a CVR, the number of total coliform bacteria (TCB) decreased nearly 100,000 times, the number of thermotolerant bacteria (TCB) by 60,000 times, and the number of coliphages (bacterial viruses) by 80 times. The most effective method for destroying pathogenic microflora is considered to be a combination of various physical treatment methods on the treated liquid. The combined use of cavitation, ultraviolet irradiation, and saturation of the liquid with ozone and oxygen provides a synergistic effect and significantly increases the effectiveness of liquid disinfection. The method of cavitation disinfection of liquids can be effectively used in the treatment of wastewater from industrial enterprises, municipal wastewater treatment plants, pool sanitation, fluid regeneration, and other liquids with which people come into contact or are discharged into the environment.",
          cavT3P2: "Use of the Cavitation Method for Wastewater Treatment and Pollution Prevention",
          cavT4: "Applications of Cavitation",
          cavT4P1: "Cavitation treatment has a wide range of applications in industry, agriculture, and medicine. In the <strong>food industry</strong>, it is used for homogenization and pasteurization of milk, conservation of food emulsions, and extending the shelf life of products.",
          cavT4P2: "In <strong>medicine</strong>, it is also used for bacteriological disinfection, as well as for the effective delivery of medicinal substances to the center of infection. It improves blood circulation and stimulates regenerative processes.",
          cavT4P3: "In <strong>agriculture</strong>, the use of cavitation-treated water results in a significant increase in yields and a reduction in crop disease, which is associated with the higher oxygen content in the water.",
          cavT4P4: "No less significant is the role of cavitation in <strong>the oil industry</strong>‚Äîcavitation treatment alters the percentage of light and heavy fractions during the cracking process in favor of the lighter ones.",
          cavT4P5: "<strong>Its application in other fields</strong>: cavitation technology involves cleaning and polishing the internal surfaces of equipment, removing contaminants and scale, producing biogas, as well as heating rooms.",
          cavT5: "Comparative Analysis and Advantages",
          cavT5P1: "<strong>1.</strong> Chlorination: This method is the most common because chlorine is relatively inexpensive. Disadvantages: Some bacteria and virus eggs are resistant to low concentrations of chlorination. Additionally, chlorination of drinking water causes changes in the genetic basis and increases the toxicity to the human body.",
          cavT5P2: "<strong>2.</strong> Ultraviolet (UV) Treatment: This method does not use chemical agents and is environmentally friendly. Disadvantages include the requirement for high transparency of the water being treated, and the absence of algae, mold, and other microorganisms.",
          cavT5P3: "<strong>3.</strong> The cavitation treatment method does not have the aforementioned drawbacks. It is much more energy-efficient and cost-effective. The costs of the cavitation method compared to other water purification methods are as follows: UV treatment - 1.7 times less, chlorination - 3.5 times less, ozonation - 10 times less.",
          cavT6: "Comparative Results of Studies on Water Disinfection Methods",
          cavT6P1: "~ The degree of disinfection is achieved as follows (<strong>with cavitation</strong>):",
          cavT6P2: "~ The degree of disinfection is achieved as follows (<strong>without cavitation</strong>):",
          cavT6P3: "Thus, under the influence of cavitation treatment on water, it is repeatedly subjected to thermobaric and electromagnetic effects. The \"cold boiling\" method of water does not require the use of additional reagents or sorbents.",
          cavT6P4: "Repeated studies have demonstrated the high effectiveness of the bactericidal action of hydrodynamic cavitation with minimal energy and economic costs.",
